@Giacomo: thank you so much for featuring Kidfresh on OpenIDEO, we both are on the same journey to provide kids with better food! As mentioned in your post, we primarily had a store in NYC where we gained tremendous experience on natural and organic kids food, including our own, freshly prepared in our kitchen. Then we decided to reach more people and now we offer nutritious frozen meals for kids directly in supermarket throughout the US. (you can check out www.kidfresh.com/find-a-store ).
@Demian Repucci: Thanks for your comment! As parents, we know how hard it can be to make children eat vegetables. We help parents provide recommended intake of veggies to their children, even when they do not have time to cook or when their kids are asking for their favorite meals, such as mac and cheese. Our nutritious, convenient and yummy meals are designed to be one part of the solution to healthier and happier kids. Its our passion and we hope youll enjoy our meals!
@Sascha: No need to be a chef, we made it easy! You just have to look for us in the frozen aisle of your local supermarket :)
Matt CohenKidfresh - www.kidfresh.com

@LoraceThank you, I am not aware of those kits. What you say is very important: One needs to find a way (through packaging and communication) to make those kits relative for children
@KyleThank you!
@DaylinThanks for adding this! I checked www.earthbox.com. What could be done is to repackage the kits and add engaging instructions with pictures and colors exactly the same way a toy industry would do. Growing your own edibles should become more fun & educational.

@Arjan: Thanks! I agree the concept of creating apparel might appeal more to girls  then boys. That slant was on purpose. I'd read an article discussing how teenage girls are the group with the most unhealthy eating habits and decided to create a concept to address the gender issues. (http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/2010/feb/09/teenage-girls-unhealthy-diet)
As you pointed out however, this problem could be addressed by extending the concept to include other types of design. As long as kids are engaging in the design process and learning about the about the benefits fresh fruits and vegetables, I think this concept would be a step in the right direction. Introducing kids to the concept that they can design objects ie., have more control over the products they own and use,  is one important outcome of this concept.
@ Jeremy : Thanks for the feedback. Waste is an important consideration. Making composting part of the program could help with this issue. An alternative would be to scale down the design to create smaller accessories: watches, shoes or jewelry. I wanted to use fresh foods because that's when they have the most colour and strongest smell. If the fresh food aspect is kept, the food could be given to a local animal shelter. You 've got me thinking about the concept could tweaked, though which is a good thing.
